# Markdown Rendering Style Improvements

Match CLI terminal output to website screenshot aesthetic.

## Part 1: Inline Code Spans — Cyan + Background

**Files:** `src/lib/formatters/colors.ts`, `src/lib/formatters/markdown.ts`

### colors.ts
Add two new color constants to `COLORS`:
```ts
/** Background tint for inline code spans (dark teal, pairs with cyan text) */
codeBg: "#1a2f3a",
/** Foreground color for inline code spans */
codeFg: "#22d3ee",
```

### markdown.ts — `renderOneInline()` (line 331)
Change codespan rendering from plain yellow to cyan-on-tinted-background with padding:
```ts
// Before:
case "codespan":
  return chalk.hex(COLORS.yellow)((token as Tokens.Codespan).text);

// After:
case "codespan":
  return chalk.bgHex(COLORS.codeBg).hex(COLORS.codeFg)(
    ` ${(token as Tokens.Codespan).text} `
  );
```

The space padding around the text creates the "pill" look matching the website's
`.code { padding: 0.1rem 0.3rem }` CSS.

## Part 2: Header Emphasis — Bold Underline + Divider Bar

**File:** `src/lib/formatters/markdown.ts` (lines 440-451)

### Heading rendering changes:
- **h1/h2**: Bold + underline cyan, followed by a short colored divider bar
- **h3**: Bold cyan (currently not bold)

```ts
// Before:
case "heading": {
  const t = token as Tokens.Heading;
  const text = renderInline(t.tokens);
  const styled =
    t.depth <= 2
      ? chalk.hex(COLORS.cyan).bold(text)
      : chalk.hex(COLORS.cyan)(text);
  parts.push(styled);
  parts.push("");
  break;
}

// After:
case "heading": {
  const t = token as Tokens.Heading;
  const text = renderInline(t.tokens);
  if (t.depth <= 2) {
    parts.push(chalk.hex(COLORS.cyan).bold(text));
    // Colored divider bar under h1/h2 for visual weight
    parts.push(chalk.hex(COLORS.cyan)("━".repeat(Math.min(stringWidth(text), 30))));
  } else {
    parts.push(chalk.hex(COLORS.cyan).bold(text));
  }
  parts.push("");
  break;
}
```

Need to add `import stringWidth from "string-width";` at top of markdown.ts
(already used by text-table.ts, same dep).

